 @fastfed  Dude, you cannot make that statement while running a 7900xtx.

"Bruh, I can play any new game on my barely 2yr old $1000 24GB VRAM GPU. which btw is still the most powerful AMD ever produced that can still compete with a 4090 in rasterized rendering, I don't understand how any other PC gamer could be having a negative experience with the latest AAA releases?".   Could you be more out of touch? 

The majority of people complaining and making these statements are the historical $350-$500 70 series (including Ti's and supers) gamers, likely still rocking a 2070 or 3070 series 8GB VRAM card, and trust me that the community is absolutely seeing issues with 8GB VRAM and less with modern game titles. These same people were likely willing to accept a $250-$300 inflation hike since their last 70 series purchase to get a 5070 Ti thinking it would be justified if it meant stepping into a 16GB card that they could get 5-6 years of solid 1440p and light 4K gaming out of, even as titles continue to grow more intensive / less optimized. You and your 7900 XTX couldn't be further from understanding where these people are coming from when they make those statements, your massive GPU will easily smoke AAA titles at 4K for another 5 years (without heavy ray tracing), and likely at 1440p for 7+ years (without heavy ray tracing).

 @JakeOrion  I remember exactly when PC prices took a nose dive. I spent over 3 grand for my first system in the 90s and just 9 months later I could build the same system for $1200. Now we seem to be creeping back to early 90s pricing but with no excuse to warrant it outside of pure greed. Motherboards are doubled, GPUs are tripled, CPUs are doubled. IDC how good it is for games $500 is way too much for an 8 core CPU in 2025. Inflation is bad but it's not that bad.

AMD and Nvidia used to survive happily on 25% margins for years, but ever since crypto they don't want to sell anything unless they're guaranteed at least 50% margins. Someone needs to slap them upside the head and remind them that you make far MORE selling millions of GPUs instead of hundreds of thousands.

While everyone loves to say Nvidia only cares about AI anymore, consumer GPUs still account for 15% of their revenue. If people don't think 15% is a big deal we can see how they feel if THEY got a 15% pay cut.

 @trizkial7592  the 3080ti is VERY close to the 3090 so it should be about the same amount of upgrade for you as it was for me. So far, I do have to say that this card is STRONG. I can run path-traced cyberpunk with XESS quality at about 60 fps. Couple that with AMD's Fluid Motion Frames 2 and anti-lag, it's a VERY smooth experience giving me 100fps.

My only complaints so far are that temps are a bit higher than with my 3080ti (about 75 Celsius average under heavy load with a slight undervolt, while 3080ti never got above 70 Celsius at any point since I've owned it) and my biggest issue is the fan noise... I got the Sapphire Pulse so not sure if that makes a difference but these fans are LOUD compared to the tuf 3080ti. 3080ti can hit 100% fan speed with barely any noise at all while the 7900XTX is twice the volume or more at 40% fan speed... 

Volume is extremely important to me so I may end up returning this card. I'm gonna wait for the 9070XT release and give that a shot if it's close to the 7900XTX. if not, I might just get a 5080 when I have the chance, even though I don't want to support Nvidia's greed anymore.

